<h2 data-section-id=3D"1sq9p5x" data-start=3D"42" data-end=3D"85">Represent=
ative pictures of each tag type</h2>
<h3 data-section-id=3D"1dlm3bn" data-start=3D"87" data-end=3D"115"><span ro=
le=3D"text">1. <strong data-start=3D"94" data-end=3D"115">RFID adhesive tag=
</strong></span></h3>
<p data-start=3D"116" data-end=3D"294">The first image shows a <strong data=
-start=3D"140" data-end=3D"175">passive UHF RFID adhesive label</strong>. T=
his is the classic =E2=80=9Csmart sticker=E2=80=9D form: very thin, no batt=
ery, and usually used for inventory or checkpoint reads.</p>
<h3 data-section-id=3D"1cvu282" data-start=3D"296" data-end=3D"323"><span r=
ole=3D"text">2. <strong data-start=3D"303" data-end=3D"323">NFC adhesive ta=
g</strong></span></h3>
<p data-start=3D"324" data-end=3D"487">The second image shows <strong data-=
start=3D"347" data-end=3D"367">NFC sticker tags</strong>. These are also th=
in adhesive labels, but they are meant for <strong data-start=3D"429" data-=
end=3D"465">very short-range tap interaction</strong>, often with a phone.<=
/p>
<h3 data-section-id=3D"mt2o3n" data-start=3D"489" data-end=3D"516"><span ro=
le=3D"text">3. <strong data-start=3D"496" data-end=3D"516">BLE adhesive tag=
</strong></span></h3>
<p data-start=3D"517" data-end=3D"699">The third image shows a <strong data=
-start=3D"541" data-end=3D"570">BLE printable asset label</strong>. This ty=
pe is usually a thin sticker-style label with a battery inside, used for in=
door asset tracking with gateways or phones.</p>
<h3 data-section-id=3D"16a1fam" data-start=3D"701" data-end=3D"719"><span r=
ole=3D"text">4. <strong data-start=3D"708" data-end=3D"719">UWB tag</strong=
></span></h3>
<p data-start=3D"720" data-end=3D"960">The fourth image shows a <strong dat=
a-start=3D"745" data-end=3D"762">UWB asset tag</strong>. UWB tags are usual=
ly <strong data-start=3D"785" data-end=3D"812">thicker and more rugged</str=
ong> than RFID/NFC sticker tags, because they are built for <strong data-st=
art=3D"868" data-end=3D"905">high-precision indoor positioning</strong> and=
 typically include a battery and more electronics.</p>
